{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_28a653164ffejcnxUY8vjL53vf","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d759ae2c7001XYxTluFW7yfnjy","parts":[{"id":"prt_d759aeeff001nL4bJHmA4ovDyr","messageID":"msg_d759ae2c7001XYxTluFW7yfnjy","sessionID":"ses_28a653164ffejcnxUY8vjL53vf","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6dd8ccae6af542ffb30eacf9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: .. _contributing:\n2: \n3: Contributing guide\n4: ==================\n5: \n6: First off, thank you for taking the time to contribute!\n7: \n8: Below are some guidelines to help you get started.\n9: \n10: \n11: Have a question?\n12: ----------------\n13: \n14: If you have any questions, feel free to reach out:\n15: \n16: - Join our community on `Discord <https://discord.gg/ABaPnm7fDC>`_ for general chat and Q&A.\n17: - Alternatively, you can `start a discussion on GitHub <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/discussions>`_.\n18: \n19: What to know before you begin\n20: -----------------------------\n21: \n22: To understand the purpose and goals behind skrub, please read our\n23: `vision statement <https://skrub-data.org/stable/vision.html>`_.\n24: \n25: If you're interested in the research behind skrub,\n26: we encourage you to explore these papers:\n27: \n28: - `Similarity Encoding for Learning with Dirty\n29:   Categorical Variables <https://hal.inria.fr/hal-01806175>`_\n30: - `Encoding High-Cardinality String Categorical\n31:   Variables <https://hal.inria.fr/hal-02171256v4>`_.\n32: \n33: How can I contribute?\n34: ---------------------\n35: \n36: Reporting bugs\n37: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n38: \n39: Using the library is the best way to discover bugs and limitations. If you find one,\n40: please:\n41: \n42: 1. **Check if an issue already exists**\n43:    by searching the `GitHub issues <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/issues?q=is%3Aissue>`_\n44: \n45:    - If **open**, leave a 👍 on the original message to signal that you are also affected.\n46:    - If closed, check for one of the following:\n47:       - A **merged pull request** may indicate the bug is fixed. Update your\n48:         skrub version or note if the fix is pending a release.\n49:       - A **wontfix label** or reasoning may be provided if the issue was\n50:         closed without a fix.\n51: 2. If the issue does not exist, `create a new one <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/issues/new>`_.\n52: \n53: How to submit a bug report?\n54: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n55: \n56: To help us resolve the issue quickly, please include:\n57: \n58: - A **clear and descriptive title**.\n59: - A **summary of the expected result**.\n60: - Any **additional details** where the bug might occur or doesn't occur unexpectedly.\n61: - A **code snippet** that reproduces the issue, if applicable.\n62: - **Version information** for Python, skrub, and relevant dependencies (e.g., scikit-learn, numpy, pandas).\n63: \n64: How to write an example?\n65: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n66: We highly encourage contributors to add examples to the documentation\n67: when they add new features, or if they have a use case that is not yet covered\n68: in the documentation.\n69: \n70: You can find a guide on how to write examples in the :ref:`example guide <tutorial_write_example>`.\n71: \n72: \n73: Suggesting enhancements\n74: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n75: \n76: If you have an idea for improving skrub, whether it's a fix\n77: or a new feature, first:\n78: \n79: - **Check if it has been proposed or implemented** by reviewing\n80:   `open pull requests <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/pulls?q=is%3Apr>`_.\n81: - If not, `submit a new issue <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/issues/new>`_\n82:   with your proposal before writing any code.\n83: \n84: How to submit an enhancement proposal?\n85: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n86: \n87: When proposing an enhancement:\n88: \n89: - **Use a clear and descriptive title**.\n90: - **Explain the goal** of the enhancement.\n91: - Provide a **detailed step-by-step description** of the proposed change.\n92: - **Link to any relevant resources** that may support the enhancement.\n93: \n94: \n95: If the enhancement proposal is validated\n96: ''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''\n97: \n98: Once your enhancement proposal is approved, let the maintainers know the following:\n99: \n100: - **If you will write the code and submit a Pull Request (PR)**:\n101:   Contributing the feature yourself is the quickest way to see it implemented.\n102:   We're here to guide you through the process if needed! To get started,\n103:   refer to the section :ref:`writing-your-first-pull-request`.\n104: - **If you won't be writing the code**:\n105:   A developer can then take over the implementation.\n106:   However, please note that we cannot guarantee how long\n107:   it will take for the feature to be added.\n108: \n109: \n110: If the enhancement is refused\n111: '''''''''''''''''''''''''''''\n112: \n113: Although many ideas are great, not all will align with the objectives\n114: of skrub.\n115: \n116: If your enhancement is not accepted, consider implementing it\n117: as a separate package that builds on top of skrub!\n118: \n119: We would love to see your work, and in some cases, we might even\n120: feature your package in the official repository.\n121: \n122: \n123: .. _writing-your-first-pull-request:\n124: \n125: Writing your first Pull Request\n126: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n127: \n128: Preparing the ground\n129: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n130: \n131: \n132: Before writing any code, make sure you have discussed your plans with the maintainers.\n133: You can do this by opening a new issue to discuss a specific improvement (as\n134: described above), or by commenting on an existing issue to express your interest in working on it.\n135: \n136: Be sure to get approval from the maintainers before you start coding, and especially\n137: before opening any new pull requests (PRs). This helps prevent issues such as multiple\n138: people working on the same problem independently, or working on an issue that is\n139: not clearly defined. Without prior discussion, your PR may be closed for being out\n140: of scope or unrelated to the problem at hand.\n141: \n142: Every PR should link to the issue it addresses.\n143: \n144: Setting up the environment\n145: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n146: \n147: To setup your development environment, you need to follow the steps in \"From Source\" tab\n148: present in :ref:`Installing from source<installing_from_source>` page.\n149: After that, you can return to this page to continue.\n150: \n151: Now that the development environment is ready, you may create a new branch and start working on\n152: the new issue.\n153: \n154: .. code:: sh\n155: \n156:    # fetch latest updates and start from the current head\n157:    git fetch upstream\n158:    git checkout -b my-branch-name-eg-fix-issue-123\n159:    # make some changes\n160:    git add ./the/file-i-changed\n161:    git commit -m \"my message\"\n162:    git push --set-upstream origin my-branch-name-eg-fix-issue-123\n163: \n164: At this point, if you visit again the `pull requests\n165: page <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/pulls>`__ github should show a\n166: banner asking if you want to open a pull request from your new branch.\n167: \n168: \n169: .. _implementation guidelines:\n170: \n171: Implementation Guidelines\n172: ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n173: \n174: When contributing, keep these project goals in mind:\n175: \n176: - **Pure Python code**: Avoid using binary extensions, Cython, or other compiled languages.\n177: - **Production-friendly code**:\n178:     - Target the widest possible range of Python versions and dependencies.\n179:     - Minimize the use of external dependencies.\n180:     - Ensure backward compatibility as much as possible.\n181: - **Performance over readability**:\n182:   Optimized code may be less readable, so please include clear and detailed comments.\n183:   Refer to this `best practice guide <https://stackoverflow.blog/2021/12/23/best-practices-for-writing-code-comments/>`_.\n184: - **Explicit variable/function names**: Use descriptive, verbose names for clarity.\n185: - **Document public API components**:\n186:     - Document all public functions, methods, variables, and class signatures.\n187:     - The public API refers to all components available for import and use by library users. Anything that doesn't begin with an underscore is considered part of the public API.\n188: \n189: Checking the quality of your code contribution\n190: ----------------------------------------------\n191: \n192: Testing the code\n193: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n194: \n195: Tests for files in a given folder should be located in a sub-folder\n196: named ``tests``: tests for skrub objects are located in ``skrub/tests/``,\n197: tests for the dataframe API are in ``skrub/_dataframe/tests/`` and so on.\n198: \n199: Tests should check all functionalities of the code that you are going to\n200: add. If needed, additional tests should be added to verify that other\n201: objects behave correctly.\n202: \n203: Consider an example: your contribution is for the\n204: ``AmazingTransformer``, whose code is in\n205: ``skrub/_amazing_transformer.py``. The ``AmazingTransformer`` is added\n206: as one of the default transformers for ``TableVectorizer``.\n207: \n208: As such, you should add a new file testing the functionality of\n209: ``AmazingTransformer`` in ``skrub/tests/test_amazing_transformer.py``,\n210: and update the file ``skrub/tests/test_table_vectorizer.py`` so that it\n211: takes into account the new transformer.\n212: \n213: Additionally, you might have updated the internal dataframe API in\n214: ``skrub/_dataframe/_common.py`` with a new function,\n215: ``amazing_function``. In this case, you should also update\n216: ``skrub/_dataframe/tests/test_common.py`` to add a test for the\n217: ``amazing_function``.\n218: \n219: Run each updated test file using ``pytest``\n220: (`pytest docs <https://docs.pytest.org/en/stable>`_):\n221: \n222: .. code:: sh\n223: \n224:    pytest -vsl skrub/tests/test_amazing_transformer.py \\\n225:    skrub/_dataframe/tests/test_common.py \\\n226:    skrub/_dataframe/tests/test_table_vectorizer.py\n227: \n228: The ``-vsl`` flag provides more information when running the tests.\n229: \n230: It is also possible to run a specific test, or set of tests using the\n231: commands ``pytest the_file.py::the_test``, or\n232: ``pytest the_file.py -k 'test_name_pattern'``. This is helpful to avoid\n233: having to run all the tests.\n234: \n235: If you work on Windows, you might have some issues with the working\n236: directory if you use ``pytest``, while ``python -m pytest ...`` should\n237: be more robust.\n238: \n239: Once you are satisfied with your changes, you can run all the tests to make sure\n240: that your change did not break code elsewhere:\n241: \n242: .. code:: sh\n243: \n244:     pytest -s skrub/tests\n245: \n246: Finally, sync your changes with the remote repository and wait for CI to run.\n247: \n248: Checking coverage on the local machine\n249: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n250: \n251: Checking coverage is one of the operations that is performed after\n252: submitting the code. As this operation may take a long time online, it\n253: is possible to check whether the code coverage is high enough on your\n254: local machine.\n255: \n256: Run your tests with the ``--cov`` and ``--cov-report`` arguments:\n257: \n258: .. code:: sh\n259: \n260:    pytest -vsl skrub/tests/test_amazing_transformer.py --cov=skrub --cov-report=html\n261: \n262: This will create the folder ``htmlcov``: by opening\n263: ``htmlcov/index.html`` it is possible to check what lines are covered in\n264: each file.\n265: \n266: Updating doctests\n267: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n268: \n269: If you alter the default behavior of an object, then this might affect\n270: the docstrings. Check for possible problems by running\n271: \n272: .. code:: sh\n273: \n274:    pytest skrub/path/to/file\n275: \n276: \n277: Formatting and pre-commit checks\n278: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n279: \n280: Formatting the code well helps with code development and maintenance,\n281: which why is skrub requires that all commits follow a specific set of\n282: formatting rules to ensure code quality.\n283: \n284: Luckily, these checks are performed automatically by the ``pre-commit``\n285: tool (`pre-commit docs <https://pre-commit.com>`__) before any commit\n286: can be pushed. Something worth noting is that if the ``pre-commit``\n287: hooks format some files, the commit will be canceled: you will have to\n288: stage the changes made by ``pre-commit`` and commit again.\n289: \n290: Ensuring the documentation builds\n291: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n292: \n293: ..\n294:   Inspired by: https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/blob/main/doc/developers/contributing.rst\n295: \n296: First, make sure you have properly installed the development version of skrub.\n297: You can follow the :ref:`installation_instructions` > \"From source\" section, if needed.\n298: \n299: To build the documentation, you need to be in the ``doc`` folder:\n300: \n301: .. code:: bash\n302: \n303:     cd doc\n304: \n305: To generate the full documentation, including the example gallery,\n306: run the following command:\n307: \n308: .. code:: bash\n309: \n310:     make html\n311: \n312: On Windows, use:\n313: \n314: .. code:: bat\n315: \n316:     make.bat html\n317: \n318: .. note::\n319: \n320:    If you are working on Windows, building the example ``1131_optuna_choices``\n321:    may fail with a permission error when running ``make.bat html``. This is\n322:    because optuna uses symlinks for file locking, which requires admin\n323:    privileges on Windows by default. The rest of the documentation build\n324:    should run without problem, so it is safe to ignore this error if your\n325:    contribution does not touch that particular example.\n326: \n327: The documentation will be generated in the ``_build/html/`` directory\n328: and are viewable in a web browser, for instance by opening the local\n329: ``_build/html/index.html`` file.\n330: \n331: Running all the examples can take a while, so if you only want to generate\n332: specific examples, you can use the following command with a regex pattern:\n333: \n334: .. code:: bash\n335: \n336:     make html EXAMPLES_PATTERN=your_regex_goes_here\n337: \n338: On Windows, use:\n339: \n340: .. code:: bat\n341: \n342:     make.bat html EXAMPLES_PATTERN=your_regex_goes_here\n343: \n344: This is especially helpful when you're only modifying or checking a few examples.\n345: \n346: It is also possible to build the documentation without running the examples\n347: without running the examples by using the following command:\n348: \n349: .. code:: bash\n350: \n351:     make html-noplot\n352: \n353: On Windows, use:\n354: \n355: .. code:: bat\n356: \n357:     make.bat html-noplot\n358: \n359: This command generates the documentation without re-executing the examples, which can\n360: take a long time. This is useful if you are only modifying the documentation itself, such as fixing\n361: typos or improving explanations.\n362: \n363: \n364: **Using pixi**\n365: \n366: You can download and install pixi from `here <https://pixi.sh/latest/>`_.\n367: \n368: From the repository root:\n369: \n370: .. code:: bash\n371: \n372:     # Build documentation without running examples (faster)\n373:     pixi run build-doc-quick\n374: \n375:     # Build the full documentation, including examples\n376:     pixi run build-doc\n377: \n378:     # Clean previously built documentation\n379:     pixi run clean-doc\n380: \n381: The documentation will be generated in the ``doc/_build/html/`` directory.\n382: You can view it by opening the local ``doc/_build/html/index.html`` file.\n383: \n384: .. warning::\n385: \n386:    On Intel-based macOS systems (``osx-64``), some pixi environments may not\n387:    resolve correctly due to missing upstream package builds (e.g., for PyTorch).\n388:    If you encounter issues, you can always fall back to using ``make`` as\n389:    described above.\n390: \n391: Editing the API reference documentation\n392: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n393: \n394: **All public functions and classes must be documented in the API\n395: reference**, hence when adding a public function or class, a new entry must be\n396: added, as detailed just above.\n397: \n398: To add a new entry to the :ref:`API reference documentation<api_ref>` or change its\n399: content, head to ``doc/api_reference.py``. This data is then used by ``doc/conf.py``\n400: to render templates located at ``doc/reference/*.rst.template``.\n401: \n402: \n403: Submitting your code\n404: --------------------\n405: \n406: Once you have pushed your commits to your remote repository, you can submit\n407: a PR by clicking the \"Compare & pull request\" button on GitHub,\n408: targeting the skrub repository.\n409: \n410: Updating the changelog\n411: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n412: Any user-facing change to the codebase needs to be reported in the changelog,\n413: found in the ``CHANGES.rst`` file in the root of the repository. A user-facing\n414: change is any change to a functionality of skrub that users are expected to interact\n415: with: for example, adding or removing a parameter, adding a new transformer,\n416: deprecating a function, etc.\n417: \n418: Changes made in the test suite, or changes made in the\n419: private parts of the library, should not be reported, unless they bring some benefit\n420: to the user (such as performance improvements). Normally, changes made to the\n421: documentation, such as typo or formatting fixes, are not reported either, while\n422: new examples usually can be added.\n423: Depending on the nature of the PR, a maintainer may add the \"no\n424: changelog needed\" label to skip the corresponding check if a changelog entry isn't\n425: relevant.\n426: \n427: Changelog entries need to follow a specific format: the change should be described\n428: in sufficient detail for users to understand how they may be affected, and the\n429: entry must list both the PR number and the GitHub username of the author(s) of the\n430: PR.\n431: \n432: Here is an example:\n433: \n434: .. code:: bash\n435: \n436:    - :meth:`DataOp.skb.apply` now allows passing extra named arguments to the\n437:   estimator's methods through the parameters ``fit_kwargs``, ``predict_kwargs``\n438:   etc. :pr:`1642` by :user:`Jérôme Dockès <jeromedockes>`.\n439: \n440: The PR number is reported with the directive ``:pr:`NUMBER```, and the author\n441: of the PR uses the directive ``:user:`AUTHOR NAME <GITHUB HANDLE>```.\n442: \n443: Missing changelog entries, or changelog entries that do not follow the format,\n444: will fail the changelog check in the CI.\n445: \n446: Continuous Integration (CI)\n447: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n448: After creating your PR, CI tools will run proceed to run all the tests on all\n449: configurations supported by skrub.\n450: \n451: - **Github Actions**:\n452:   Used for testing skrub across various platforms (Linux, macOS, Windows)\n453:   and dependencies.\n454: - **CircleCI**:\n455:   Builds and verifies the project documentation.\n456: \n457: If any of the following markers appears in the commit message, the following\n458: actions are taken.\n459: \n460:     ====================== ===================\n461:     Commit Message Marker  Action Taken by CI\n462:     ---------------------- -------------------\n463:     [ci skip]              CI is skipped completely\n464:     [skip ci]              CI is skipped completely\n465:     [skip github]          CI is skipped completely\n466:     [deps nightly]         CI is run with the nightly builds of dependencies\n467:     [doc skip]             Docs are not built\n468:     [doc quick]            Docs built, but excludes example gallery plots\n469:     [doc build]            Docs built including example gallery plots (longer)\n470:     ====================== ===================\n471: \n472: Note that by default the documentation is built, but only the examples that are\n473: directly modified by the pull request are executed.\n474: \n475: CI is testing all possible configurations supported by skrub, so tests may fail\n476: with configurations different from what you are developing with. If this is the\n477: case,  it is possible to run the tests in the environment that is failing by\n478: using `pixi <https://pixi.sh/latest/>`_. For example if the env is ``ci-py309-min-optional-deps``, it is\n479: possible to replicate it using the following command:\n480: \n481: .. code:: sh\n482: \n483:    pixi run -e ci-py309-min-optional-deps  pytest skrub/tests/path/to/test\n484: \n485: This command downloads the specific environment on the machine, so you can test\n486: it locally and apply fixes, or have a clearer idea of where the code is failing\n487: to discuss with the maintainers.\n488: \n489: Finally, if the remote repository was changed, you might need to run\n490:   ``pre-commit run --all-files`` to make sure that the formatting is\n491:   correct.\n492: \n493: Integration\n494: ^^^^^^^^^^^\n495: \n496: Community consensus is key in the integration process. Expect a minimum of\n497: 1 to 3 reviews from maintainers depending on the size of the change before we consider\n498: merging the PR.\n\n(End of file - total 498 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":".. _contributing:\n\nContributing guide\n==================\n\nFirst off, thank you for taking the time to contribute!\n\nBelow are some guidelines to help you get started.\n\n\nHave a question?\n----------------\n\nIf you have any questions, feel free to reach out:\n\n- Join our community on `Discord <https://discord.gg/ABaPnm7fDC>`_ for general chat and Q&A.\n- Alternatively, you can `start a discussion on GitHub <https://github.com/skrub-data/skrub/discussions>`_.\n\nWhat to know before you begin\n-----------------------------","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"CONTRIBUTING.rst","time":{"start":1775794581617,"end":1775794581622}}}]}
